{{clr}}
Mobile's&nbsp;geographical location on the [[Gulf of Mexico]] provides a mild [[subtropical]] [[climate]], with an average annual temperature of 67.5°F. January through December temperatures range from 40°F min. and 91°F max. The average annual precipitation of 66.29 inches benefits the lush vegetation of the region.<ref>http://cdo.ncdc.noaa.gov/climatenormals/clim20/ak/500352.pdf</ref><ref>Weatherbill Incorporated, 2007</ref> Mobile has warm summers with Gulf breezes and mild, wet winters. Being on the Gulf, Mobile is occasionally affected by major [[tropical storm]]s and [[hurricanes]].<ref name="srg-climate">{{cite web|title=''Mobile's Climate''|work=SeniorsResourceGuide.com|url=http://www.seniorsresourceguide.com/directories/Mobile/about_region.html|accessdate=2007-05-05}}</ref> A 2007 study by WeatherBill, Inc. determined that Mobile is the wettest city in the United States, with more than 5 feet of rainfall annually. <ref>Thompsen, Andrea (May 22, 2007) [http://www.livescience.com/environment/070518_rainy_cities.html "Study Reveals Top 10 Wettest U.S. Cities."]</ref> Snow is rare in Mobile.

===Hurricanes===
* '''Frederic''':  Mobile suffered its worst natural disaster on [[September 12]], [[1979]] when Category 3 [[Hurricane Frederic]] slammed into the heart of the city.  The storm caused tremendous damage to nearby [[Dauphin Island, Alabama|Dauphin Island]] and [[Gulf Shores, Alabama|Gulf Shores]].  The city took over 5 years to fully recover from the devastating hurricane.
* '''Ivan''':  Mobile received moderate damage from [[Hurricane Ivan]] on [[September 16]], [[2004]]. It made landfall in Gulf Shores, Alabama about 30 miles away. Mobile was caught in Ivan's western [[eye]] and the destruction was eerily similar to 1979's Frederic. Maximum winds were observed at [[U.S.S. Alabama|Battleship Park]] at 105 miles per hour. The recording equipment then stopped working. The city received 8 inches of rain in the 48 hours of Ivan's approach and passage.<ref name="HurIvan"|>{{cite web|title=" Powerful Hurricane Ivan Slams the IS Central Gulf Coast as an Upper Category-3 Storm"|work="National Weather Service Forecast Office Mobile/Pensacola"|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/mob/ivan_page/Ivan-main.htm|accessdate=2007-05-09}}</ref>
* '''Katrina''':  Mobile received moderate damage from [[Hurricane Katrina]] in August of [[2005]]. A storm surge of 11.45 feet devastated eastern parts of Mobile.  The surge may have been the highest recorded in Mobile in over 85 years.<ref name'"HurKat">{{cite web|title="Extremely Powerful Hurricane Katrina leave a Historic Mark on the Gulf Coast|work="National Weather Service Forecast Office Mobile/Pensacola" |url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/mob/0805Katrina|accessdate=2007-05-09}}</ref>

Mobile has also suffered damage from hurricanes: [[Hurricane Camille|Camille]], [[Hurricane Elena|Elena]], [[Hurricane Georges|Georges]], [[Hurricane Erin (1995)|Erin]], [[Hurricane Opal|Opal]], [[Hurricane Florence (1988)|Florence]], [[Hurricane Cindy (2005)|Cindy]] and [[Hurricane Danny (1997)|Danny]].

== Demographics ==
Mobile is the center of [[Alabama]]'s second-largest metropolitan area, which consists of all of Mobile county. [[Mobile metropolitan area|Metropolitan Mobile]] (MSA) had a population of approximately 429,622 as of 2006 census estimates.  Mobile is a part of the Mobile - Daphne - Fairhope [[Combined statistical area]] (CSA) which had a population of 588,246 according to 2006 estimates. The population of the Mobile - Fairhope - Bay Minette Combined statistical area includes the counties and populations  of Mobile (Mobile) and Baldwin (Fairhope and Bay Minette). Mobile County saw substantial population growth of nearly 24,000 people after Hurricane Katrina devastated Louisiana and Mississippi in September 2005.

As of the [[census]]{{GR|2}} of [[2000]], there were 210,915 people, 78,480 households, and 60,000 families residing in the city.  The [[population density]] was 651.4/km² (1,687.1/mi²).  There were 86,187 housing units at an average density of 282.2/km² (731.0/mi²).  The racial makeup of the city was 46.40% [[Race (US Census)|White]], 52.29% [[Race (US Census)|Black]] or [[Race (US Census)|African American]], 0.24% [[Race (US Census)|Native American]], 1.52% [[Race (US Census)|Asian]], 0.03% [[Race (US Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.53% from [[Race (US Census)|other races]], and 1.00% from two or more races.  1.42% of the population were Latino.

There were 85,000 households out of which 30.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 41.1% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 19.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 35.3% were non-families. 30.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 10.5% had someone living alone who is 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.46 and the average family size was 3.09.

In the city the population is spread out with 26.5% under the age of 18, 10.8% from 18 to 24, 28.0% from 25 to 44, 21.0% from 45 to 64, and 13.7% who are 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 34 years.  For every 100 females there were 87.8 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 82.9 males.

The median income for a household in the city was $31,445, and the median income for a family was $39,752. Males had a median income of $31,629 versus $22,051 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $18,072.  21.2% of the population and 17.9% of families were below the [[poverty line]].  Out of the total population, 31.4% of those under the age of 18 and 14.7% of those 65 and older were living below the poverty line.

==Law and government==
{{see also|Mobile, Alabama/List of mayors of Mobile}}
{{see also|Mobile, Alabama mayoral election, 2005}}

===City government===
The government of Mobile consists of a mayor and a seven member city council, operating on a weak mayor/strong council format. Municipal elections are held every 4 years. The current mayor, [[Sam Jones (mayor)|Sam Jones]], was elected in September of 2005 and is the first [[African American]] mayor of Mobile.<ref name="democrats.org>{{cite web|title=''Dean Congratulates Sam Jones, First Black Mayor of Mobile, Alabama on Victory''|work="Democrats.org|url=http://www.democrats.org/a/2005/09/dean_congratula.php|date=2005-09-16|accessdate=2007-05-09}}</ref>

===Public safety===
*The Mobile Police Department serves as primary law-enforcement in the city of Mobile and is divided into the main headquarters, 5 precincts, and 3 mini-stations.
*The Mobile Fire-Rescue Department provides fire protection, fire investigation, hazardous materials assessment and clean-up, and back-up emergency ambulance service in the city of Mobile.
*The Mobile County Emergency Management Agency has the primary responsibility for development of plans to provide protection for all citizens and property in all emergencies that may affect Mobile county, includes the city of Mobile.

==Economy==
[[Image:Mobile Alabama harbor aerial view.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of the port of Mobile.]] 

Over the past 5 years Mobile's economy has been expanding.  Numerous local, national, and  international companies are funneling over $9 billion into the city.  Mobile's unemployment rate is 5.1% and has been declining for 2 years straight.  Due to the numerous new industries coming online in Mobile over the next three to five years, Mobile is projected to have an unemployment rate of less than 2.0% by the 4th quarter of 2010. 

Mobile's [[Port of Mobile|Alabama State Docks]] is currently undergoing the largest expansion in its history by expanding its container processing and storage facility and increasing container storage at the docks by over 1,000%. <ref>{{web cite|title="ALABAMA SENATE APPROVES  		PORT FUNDING - ALABAMA STATE PORT AUTHORITY POISED TO LET NEW CONTAINER  		TERMINAL CONTRACTS"|work="Alabama State Port Authority|date=[[2005-05-17]]|url=http://www.asdd.com/Asd/news47.htm|accessdate=2007-05-09}}</ref> Mobile is also in the race to become home to the nations largest military contract in history, a $200+ billion [[Aerial refueling|tanker aircraft]] project for the armed forces which would generate over 5,000 high paying jobs in Mobile.  The project would be with [[EADS]] North America.  The rapidly growing [[auto industry]] in Alabama has also resulted in over 2,800 new jobs created in Mobile.    
[[Image:GMOTerminal.jpg|thumb|left|[[Gulf, Mobile and Ohio Railroad|The Gulf, Mobile, and Ohio]] Depot (1907) at Water and Beauregard Streets was recently restored and converted to office space.]]
In 2001, the Mobile City Council approved a deal with the [[Retirement Systems of Alabama]] for a complete restoration of the historic [[Battle House Hotel]], as well as construction of the [[RSA Battle House Tower|Battle House Tower]], a 35-story, 745-foot (227 m) tall [[skyscraper]] which is now the tallest building in Alabama. <ref>Jumper, Kathy, ''Massive undertaking required several contractors to finish Massive undertaking a multi-contractor job'', Mobile Register, [[May 6, 2007]], page L10</ref>  The Battle House Project is part of the "String of Pearls" initiative undertaken by the administration of former Mayor Mike Dow (1989-2005), which saw the construction of the [[Arthur C. Outlaw Convention Center]] on Water Street,  the [[Alabama Cruise Terminal]] on Water Street, the approval of the soon to be constructed [[Maritime Museum of the Gulf of Mexico]], and the rebirth of Dauphin Street, Mobile's historic commercial corridor. 

In 2007, [[Germany|German]] steel manufacturer [[ThyssenKrupp]] announced plans for a $4.2 billion  steel mill. The new plant is currently under construction in northern [[Mobile County, Alabama|Mobile County]].  Company officials say 2,700 permanent jobs will be added to the local economy. <ref> ''Mobile County Wins ThyssenKrupp Plant,'' [http://blog.al.com/live/2007/05/mobile_county_wins_thyssenkrup.html Press Register, 11-May 2007]</ref>  In the 20 months after the Katrina disaster, Mobile saw a housing boom of more than 3,500 new homes built, exceeding even the post World War II boom of the late 1940s.

==Education==
Public schools in Mobile are operated by the [[Mobile County Public School System]].  The Mobile school system finished a $175 million new construction project in 2005.

The State of Alabama operates the [[Alabama School of Mathematics and Science]], which boards advanced Alabama high school students. 

In addition to the public school system, there are also a large number of private schools, many of them belonging to the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Mobile]]. The most notable private institutions include [[McGill-Toolen Catholic High School]], [[St. Paul's Episcopal School]], [[UMS-Wright Preparatory School]], [[Mobile Christian School]], [[Faith Academy (Mobile, Alabama)|Faith Academy]] and [[Cottage Hill Christian Academy]]. 

Higher eduation in the Mobile area features '''The [[University of South Alabama]]''', '''[[Spring Hill College]]''', '''The [[University of Mobile]]''', '''[[Bishop State Community College]]''', and '''[[Faulkner State Community College]]'''.

==Arts and entertainment==
===Culture=== 
[[Image:Saenger Theatre Mobile.jpg|thumb|left|Mobile Saenger Theatre (1927) on South Joachim Street.]]
Mobile has a variety of cultural venues and events.
*The [[Mobile Carnival Museum]], which houses the city's [[Mardi Gras in Mobile|Mardi Gras]] history and memorabilia, is designed to document the variety of floats and displays seen during the festival season.<ref> Andrews, Casandra, ''"Master of make-Believe"'', Press Register, Mobile, Alabama: January 28, 2007 </ref>

*The [[National African American Archives]] is located in the former Davis Avenue branch of the Mobile Public Library.<ref> [http://nationalafricanamericanarchives.org/Pages/about.htm National African American Archives, Retrieved May 5, 2007] </ref>

*The historic [[Saenger Theatre (Mobile, Alabama)|Saenger Theatre]] of Mobile was opened in 1927 as part of a chain of theaters across the nation.  The interior was designed in a Greek mythology style with thought given to Mobile's coastal location. <ref> [http://www.mobilesaenger.com/history.php Mobile Saenger Theater History, Retrieved May 5, 2007]</ref>
*The city is home to the [[Mobile Arts Council]], the [[Mobile Symphony]], and the [[Mobile Ballet]]. <ref name="srg-cultural">{{cite web|title=''Cultural''|work=SeniorsResourceGuide.com|url=http://www.seniorsresourceguide.com/directories/Mobile/about_region.html|accessdate=2007-05-05}}</ref> 
 
*The city hosts the 60-year old [[Mobile Opera]] which averages about 1,200 in attendance through the year. The [[Mobile Opera]] also supports the Rose Palmai-Tenser Scholarship competition which is held in late May. <ref>{{cite web|title=''Setting the Stage: Mobile Opera offers a three show season for 2007-08''|work=Press Register|url=http://www.al.com/entertainment/press-register/index.ssf?/base/entertainment/1179048222106610.xml&coll=3&thispage=1|accessdate 2007-05-16}}</ref>

*In 2007 the historic Battle House Hotel was restored and reopened after falling into disuse for over 30 years. The hotel was originally built in 1852 and was destroyed by fire twice. Rebuilt for the third time in 1908 it is now part of the project overseen by the [[Retirement Systems of Alabama]].  It was the scene of many of Mobile's balls and cultural events in the past.
[[Image:A543288759 2074a6e360 o.jpg|thumb|[[Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception in Mobile|Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception]] (1835-84) in downtown.]]

*Mobile is home to the Azalea Trail Maids.  Girls in their junior year of high school can try out to be an [[Azalea Trail Maid]], only fifty are chosen.  To be on the court, each girl is interviewed by a panel of judges and their score is decided based upon their presentation and knowledge of important Mobile, Alabama, and World history, as well as current news.  The fifty selected Azalea Trail Maids make up the Azalea Trail Maid Court; they serve as Mobile's goodwill ambassadors and make appearances at many important events, not limited to Mobile itself.

===Cruises===
The city is home port for [[Carnival Cruise Lines]]' ''[[MS Holiday]]'' [[cruise ship]] which sails on four and five day itineraries through the Western [[Caribbean]].

===Libraries===
The [[Mobile Public Library]] system serves Mobile and consists of eight branches across Mobile County, featuring a large local history and genealogy division housed in its own new facilty next to the newly restored and enlarged Ben May Main Library on Government Street.  Mobile is also home to the Mobile Genealogical Society Library and Media Center.

===Mardi Gras===
:''Main articles: [[Mardi Gras]] and [[Mardi Gras in Mobile]].''
Mobile celebrated Mardi Gras first in [[1703]] when settlers began the festivities at the [[Old Mobile Site]]. Modern Mardi Gras in Mobile is  known for its a family-friendly celebration, in contrast to the celebration in [[New Orleans]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Susan |last=Houston |authorlink= |title=Mobile; It Has History |work=The News & Observer  |publisher=News & Observer Publishing Company, (Raleigh, NC) |date=2007-02-04 |accessdate=2007-05-22 }} </ref>  The celebration lasts for over two weeks and culminates on [[Fat Tuesday]], the day before [[Lent]]. <ref name="moborg-mg">{{cite web|title=''Mardi Gras''|work=Mobile.org|url=http://www.mobile.org/ab_mardigras.php|accessdate=2007-04-18}}</ref>

===Media===
*Mobile's ''[[Press-Register]]'' is Alabama's oldest active newspaper, dating back to [[1813]];<ref name=NHreg>
   "Newhouse News Service - The Press-Register" (description),
   Newhouse News Service, 2007, webpage:
   [http://www.newhouse.com/the-press-register.html NH-Register].   
</ref> The paper focuses on [[Mobile County, Alabama|Mobile]] and [[Baldwin County, Alabama|Baldwin]] Counties and the city of Mobile, but also serves southwest Alabama and in nearby areas of Mississippi.<ref name=NHreg/>  Mobile's alternative newspaper is the ''[[Lagniappe (pamphlet)|Lagniappe]]''.  The Mobile area is served by [http://www.mobilebaymonthly.com ''Mobile Bay Monthly''] magazine.

*Mobile is served locally by [[WPMI-TV|WPMI]] ([[NBC]]), [[WKRG]] ([[CBS]]), and [[WALA]] ([[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]]) television stations. The regional area is also served by [[WEAR-TV|WEAR]] ([[ABC-TV|ABC]]) based in [[Pensacola, Florida]]. [[WJTC]], also known as UTV 44, is an independent station serving Mobile and Pensacola.

*The Mobile area is served by 12 [[FM broadcasting|FM]] radio stations.
[[Image:Close Encounters poster.jpg|thumb|Mobile was a primary filming location in ''
[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]'']]
{{Main|List of radio stations in Mobile}}

===Museums===
Mobile's art and history museums include the [[Mobile Museum of Art]], the [[Oakleigh]] Historic Complex, the [[Museum of Mobile]], and [[Battleship Memorial Park]]. The [[Dauphin Island Sea Lab]] is located south of the city near the mouth of [[Mobile Bay]]. The [[Bragg-Mitchell Mansion]] and the [[Conde-Charlotte House]] are historic house museums. The [[Magee farmhouse]] figures into local [[American Civil War]] history.  Other unique museums include the [[Mobile Medical Museum]], the [[Phoenix Fire Museum]], the [[Mobile Police Museum]], and the [[St. Ignatius Archives and Museum]]. <ref name="srg-arts">{{cite web|title=''Arts & History''|work=SeniorsResourceGuide.com|url=http://www.seniorsresourceguide.com/directories/Mobile/about_region.html|accessdate=2007-05-05}}</ref>

===National events===
Mobile is host to such national events as the [[Senior Bowl]] [[American football|football]] game (January), the Senior Bowl 10K, which is the national 10K road race championship, the [[Azalea Trail Run]] 10K race (March) and the [[America's Junior Miss]] Pageant (June). <ref name="moborg-culture">{{cite web|title=''Culture''|work=Mobile.org|url=http://www.mobile.org/ab_culture.php|accessdate=2007-04-18}}</ref>

===Popular culture===
{{Main|Mobile, Alabama in popular culture}}
Mobile is the subject or location for several films, songs, and books including ''[[Under Siege]]'' (1992) which was filmed on the [[USS Alabama]] in [[Battleship Memorial Park]], [[Steven Spielberg|Steven Spielberg's]] ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]'' (1977) which was filmed in various Mobile locations, [[Jimmy Buffett]]'s "Stars Fell on Alabama", [[Bob Dylan]]'s "Stuck Inside of Mobile with the Memphis Blues Again" and [[Richard Bradford|Richard Bradford's]] novel [[Red Sky at Morning (Bradford novel)|''Red Sky at Morning'']].  Mobile features prominently in the [[PBS]] [[WWII]] documentary [[The War (documentary)|''The War'']] (2007) by [[Ken Burns]].

==Parks and recreation==
[[Image:Bienville.jpg|thumb|Bienville Square from Dauphin Street.]]
Mobile has many public parks, meeting facilities, and numerous sports venues for football, baseball, tennis, and golf.

===Public parks===
Some of Mobile's more notable public parks are:
*[[Bienville Square]], historic park (1850) in the Lower Dauphin Street Historic District, named for Mobile’s founder, [[Jean-Baptiste Le Moyne, Sieur de Bienville]].
*British Park, a neighborhood park located in the Church Street East Historic District, honors the British heritage of the city.
*[[Cathedral Plaza]], in the Lower Dauphin Street Historic District overlooking the [[Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception in Mobile|Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception]].
*[[Fort Condé]], the city’s official welcome center and living history museum.
*[[Langan (Municipal) Park]], 720-acre park featuring golf, tennis, outdoor concerts, a children’s playground and picnic areas. It is also home to the [[Mobile Museum of Art]], the [[Azalea City Golf Course]], [[Mobile Botanical Gardens]] and Playhouse in the Park.
*Memorial (Soldiers and Sailors) Park, honors Mobile's fallen soldiers and sailors, features a large marble colonnade monument.
*Spanish Plaza, located in the Church Street East Historic District, honors the Spanish heritage of the city.
*Washington Square, a neighborhood park located in the Oakleigh Garden Historic Distric, known for its large [[live oak]]s.

===Recreation===
For more information on sports in Mobile see:
{{Main|Mobile sports history}}
*Mobile is the home of [[Ladd-Peebles Stadium]]. The [[American football|football]] stadium opened in [[1948]] with [[University of Alabama|Alabama]] and [[Vanderbilt University|Vanderbilt]] battling to a 14-14 tie. With a capacity of 40,646, Ladd-Peebles Stadium is the 4th largest stadium in the state. <ref name="ladd">{{cite web|title=''Ladd-Peebles Stadium''|work=LaddPeeblesStadium.com|url=http://www.laddpeeblesstadium.com/default.asp|accessdate=2007-04-23}}</ref>  Ladd-Peebles Stadium has been home to the [[Senior Bowl]] since [[1951]], featuring the best college seniors in [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] football.<ref name="srbowl">{{cite web|title=''The Senior Bowl''|work=Seniorbowl.com|url=http://www.seniorbowl.com/2007/gamerecaps1950s.htm|accessdate=2007-04-23}}</ref> The [[GMAC Bowl]] has been played since [[1999]] featuring opponents from the [[Mid-American Conference]] and [[Conference USA]].<ref name="gmacbowl">{{cite web|title=''Game Recaps''|work=GMACbowl.com|url=http://www.gmacbowl.com/gamerecaps.asp|accessdate=2007-04-23}}</ref> Since [[1988]], Ladd-Peebles Stadium has hosted the Alabama-Mississippi All-Star Classic. The top graduating high school seniors from their respective states compete each June. <ref name="AMall-star">{{cite web|title=''History of the Alabama-Mississippi All-Star Classic''|work=ahsaasports.com|url=http://www.ahsaasports.com/football/alms-allstar/history.asp|accessdate=2007-04-23}}</ref>

*For golfers, Magnolia Grove, part of the [[Robert Trent Jones Golf Trail]], has  36 holes. The Falls course was recently named the best par 3 course in America. <ref name="rtj">{{cite web|title=''Magnolia Grove''|work=RTJgolf.com|url=http://www.rtjgolf.com/courses/magnolia_grove/|accessdate=2007-05-05}}</ref>  Since 1999, the [[LPGA]] Tournament of Champions has been played annually at Magnolia Grove.  The Crossings course is home of this tournament. According to [[Golf Digest]], Mobile is a top ten golf area that offers year-round golfing.

*Mobile is also home to the [[Azalea Trail Run]], which races through historic midtown and downtown Mobile.  This 10k run has been an annual event since [[1978]].<ref name="com">{{cite web|title=''Event Calendar''|work=CityOfMObile.org|url=http://www.cityofmobile.org/calendar_events.php?category=&day=&month=01&year=2007|accessdate=2007-04-30}}</ref> The Azalea Trail Run is one of the premier 10k road races in the U.S., attracting runners from all over the world. <ref name="vulcan">{{cite web|title=''Azalea Trail Run''|work=VulcanTri.com|url=http://www.vulcantri.com/index.php?option=com_events&task=view_detail&agid=448&year=2006&month=03&day=25&Itemid=46|accessdate=2007-05-05}}</ref>

*Mobile is the home of [[Hank Aaron Stadium]] and hometown to five baseball Hall of Fame members ([[Hank Aaron]], [[Billy Williams (baseball player)|Billy Williams]], [[Willie McCovey]], [[Satchel Paige]], [[Ozzie Smith]]). 

*A wide variety of events are held at the Mobile's [[Arthur C. Outlaw Convention Center]].  It contains a 100,000 square-foot exhibit hall, a 15,000 square-foot grand ballroom, and sixteen meeting rooms.

*The [[Mobile Civic Center]] contains three facilities under one roof.  The 400,000 square-foot building has an arena, a theater and an exposition hall.  It is the primary concert venue for the city and also hosts a wide variety of events.

==Notable residents==
[[Image:Semmes Statue.jpg|thumb|Statue of Admiral [[Raphael Semmes]] at Government and Royal Street.]] 
A few of Mobile's more notable [[List of people from Mobile, Alabama|residents]], for all others see:
{{main|List of people from Mobile, Alabama}}
*[[Hank Aaron]], former home-run king.  [[Hank Aaron Stadium]] in Mobile is named in his honor as is the Hank Aaron Loop in downtown Mobile.
*[[Jimmy Buffett]], singer-songwriter.
*[[Joe Cain|Joseph Stillwell Cain, Jr.]], largely credited with the rebirth of [[Mardi Gras]] celebrations in Mobile after the [[American Civil War|Civil War]].
*[[Winston Groom]], novelist and non-fiction writer, best known for his book ''[[Forrest Gump]]''.
*Madame [[Octavia Walton LeVert]], [[antebellum]] travel writer and once known as "the belle of the South".
*[[Satchel Paige]], baseball pitcher and actor.  Satchel Paige Drive in Mobile is named in his honor.
*Admiral [[Raphael Semmes]], captain of the [[CSS Alabama|CSS ''Alabama'']] during the [[American Civil War]] and resident of Mobile.  The Mobile suburb of [[Semmes, Alabama|Semmes]] is named in his honor.
*[[Alva Belmont|Alva Erskine Smith Vanderbilt]], born and raised in Mobile, wife of [[William Kissam Vanderbilt|William K. Vanderbilt]]. Known for building several of the most noted houses of the [[Gilded Era]] and later a crusader for the [[women's suffrage]] movement and the [[Equal Rights Amendment]].
*[[Eugene Walter]], actor in several [[Fellini]] films and author of ''Milking the Moon''.  He was interred in the historic [[Church Street Graveyard]] by special permission of the city.

==Transportation==
[[Image:Interstate 10 eastbound in Mobile, AL.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Interstate 10 eastbound in downtown approaching the [[George Wallace Tunnel]] underneath the [[Mobile River]].]]
Local airline passengers are served by three airports: 
*[[Mobile Regional Airport|Mobile Regional]]
*[[Gulfport-Biloxi International Airport|Gulfport-Biloxi International]]
*[[Pensacola Regional Airport|Pensacola Regional]]. 

Additionally, the [[Mobile Downtown Airport]] serves corporate, cargo and private cargo aircraft and is home to major [[aeronautical]] maintenance, overhaul and repair facilities.

Highways linking Mobile to the rest of the country include [[Interstate 10]], [[Interstate 65]], [[Interstate 165 (Alabama)|Interstate 165]], [[US 31]], [[US 43]], [[US 45]], [[US 90]] and [[US 98]]. Mobile has three routes over the [[Mobile River]] and into neighboring [[Baldwin County, Alabama]]. [[Interstate 10]] travels through the [[George Wallace Tunnel]] while the [[Bankhead Tunnel]] provides transit via [[US 98]]. The [[Cochrane-Africatown USA Bridge]] is the third route and carries traffic via [[US 90]] and serves as the alternate truck and hazardous waste route for [[US 98]]. 

Mobile is served by the [http://www.thewavetransit.com/ Wave Transit] Bus System. Also, Mobile has several taxi services.

